@RozzieGrandma

The NFL has been playing several games in various foreign cities, most often in England and Germany, in the past few years, and there will be a game in Madrid in November.  They will also play in England, Ireland, Germany and Brazil. I don't know if any of it is having any effect, though.

There sure is a lot of soccer over here, though, with the Club World Cup just completed last week, and the World Cup scheduled for next year.  I have watched some soccer over the years and I have decided I'll pass on it...I find baseball and (our) football both more interesting games.  I think that the learning curve required to learn either one is steeper than for soccer, and that's why they're slow to catch on internationally, or even with non-fans over here.

@Nancy J.

My mother was not a believer in top sheets. 

I never knew that other people used them (or really, that they even existed) until I went to college.

@Warren

That's why we usually have different duvets for summer and winter. Also, many people switch a duvet for a blanket in the warmest months, dressing it in a duvet case.

We have different solutions to the same problem 🙂

@Sam Lyons
Exactly!
I sometimes sleep with only the top sheet over me--it depends on the temperature of the room (or on my own temperature!)

@Nancy J.
I’m flummoxed by all the posters who use (gasp) sheets and blankets! Over here that went out with the Dark Ages. I do remember being suffocated under layers of stuff at my Gran’s as a kid. 
We have different duvet tog ratings for the seasons. Right now we’ve got a 2.5 super lightweight one. It’s equivalent to just a top sheet I should think. We go up to 7.5 in winter, though the standard is 10 to 12 heavy weight. That’s too hot for me.

@Mean Old Lady

A light quilt - without a sheet - is my favorite for the rare hot nights we get here in northern Germany. The batting (wadding) is wool, which sounds paradoxical to use in the heat, but wool has amazing thermal properties, and I never sweat under my summer quilt. It is easily machine washable btw. 

Quilting is less well-known here than in the US, UK, Australia, New Zealand and Scandinavia, but there is an active quilting community (to which I belong). And there are some extremely talented Polish quilters!

@Nancy J.

PJs for me, long sleeved in winter, short sleeved in summer. It's very rare for peeps to sleep in the nude here. 

